As is known, iridoids and volatile oil have been recognized as the two major constituents in the genus 

Valeriana

(
Wang et al., 2009
; 
Xu et al., 2012
). And so far, nearly 110 iridoids (
Fan et al., 2020
; 
Houghton, 1988
; 
Lin et al., 2009
, 
2013
; 
Ming et al., 1997
; 
Tang et al., 2002
; 
Tomassini et al., 2005
; 
Wang et al., 2008
, 2020) have been discovered from 

Valeriana
species

, possessing numerous valuable efficacies such as sleep-promoting (
Shinjyo et al., 2020
), anti-anxiety (
Orhan, 2021
), sedative (D. 
Leathwood et al., 1982
), and anti-spasmodic (
Hattesohl et al., 2008
; 
Rezvani et al., 2010
; 
Wang et al., 2012
) activities. 

Valeriana officinalis
L

. (
Valerianaceae
) is one of the most commonly used plants in 

Valeriana

genus, and it is frequently prescribed in the form of water decoction in most traditional medicinal systems (
Bruni et al., 2021
; 
Neamati et al., 2014
; 
Sharifzadeh et al., 2006
). However, few modern phytochemical studies (
Zu et al., 2014
) focus on the water-soluble constituents of 

V. officinalis

despite the fact that modern pharmacological investigations have uncovered the significant anticonvulsant (
Rezvani et al., 2010
), anti-coronaryspastic, anti-hypertensive and anti-bronchospastic activities (
Circosta et al., 2007
) of the aqueous extracts (or water decoctions) of 

V. officinalis

.

Herein, during our preparation and chemical fingerprinting of the components of common Chinese medicines (CMs), phytochemical study on the water-soluble components of roots and rhizomes of 

V. officinalis

afforded the isolation of twenty-six compounds, including nine previously undescribed compounds (
1–9
, 
Fig. 1
) and the seventeen known ones (Supplementary Fig. S82), with structures assigned by analysis of the extensive spectroscopic data, aided by electronic circular dichroism (ECD) calculations. Furthermore, a Griess method (
Cui et al., 2018
) was applied to evaluate the anti-neuroinflammatory potentials of those isolates on the secretion of nitric oxide (NO) by LPS stimulation in BV-2 cells (
Hashioka, 2011
; 
Liu et al., 2012
; 
Ou et al., 2020
; 
Sun et al., 2020
).

deduced by analysis of their HRESIMS (Supplementary Figs. S1 and S9) and NMR ( Table 1 ) data. 1 H and 13 C NMR spectra of 1 and 2 were both composed of the characteristic proton and carbon resonances assignable to an oxygenated patchouli alcohol ( Shi et al., 2016 ), as similar in the known 8-acetoxyl-patchouli alcohol ( 11 ) ( Shi et al., 2016 ) and valeriananoid A ( 12 ) (
Fukushima et al., 2007
). As detailed in Table 1 and Figs. 2 and 3 , overall comparison of the NMR data between 1 and 2 revealed that C-3 ( δ C 76.6, a methine oxygenated by an acetoxyl group) in 1 was oxygenated instead of the C-8 ( δ C 81.4, an oxygenated methine glycosylated by a glucose) in 2 . And, the C-6’ (a hydroxymethyl with δ C 68.7) of the glucopyranosyl moiety in 2 was substituted by another apiofuranosyl moiety as indicated by comparing its NMR data with those of valeriananoid F ( 13 ) ( Tan et al., 2016 ), a known 8- O -β -D-glucopyranosyl-patchouli alcohol. The existence of D-glucose and D-apiose in 2 was confirmed by precolumn derivatization HPLC analysis of acid hydrolysate of 2 (Supplementary Fig. S80) (Fan, et al., 2019). In NOESY spectrum of 2 , the presence of correlation between H-2" ( δ H 3.89, d, J =2.4 Hz) and H-4 ′′ b ( δ H 3.95, d, J =10.2 Hz) and the absence of correlation between H-2 ′′ and H-1" ( δ H 5.00, d, J = 2.4 Hz) indicated a β -D-configuration of the apiofuranosyl moiety (Picmanova ˇ´ and Møller, 2016 ; Juliao ˜et al., 2010). And the β -configuration of the glucopyranosyl moiety was projected by the 3 J coupling constant between H-1 ′ and H-2 ′ , which was above 7.0 Hz. Thus, 1 and 2 were accordingly identified as 3-acetoxyl-patchouli alcohol and patchouli alcohol 8- O -β -D-apiofuranosyl-(1 → 6)- β -D-glucopyranoside.

Further, by comparison of the experimental spectroscopic data with those reported, the structures of other seventeen known compounds (
10–26
) were elucidated as 8-hydroxyl-patchouli alcohol (
10
) (
